<size=20>Passive Breathing</size>
v4.2

<color=#ca6fde>by Lunazera</color>

▼——————————————— ▼

This breathing loop will start on VNyan load, and is toggleable with a hotkey or websocket command. Works with Heartrate monitors, Hebi's Live2D ArmSway graph.

If you use ArmSway, you can add "breathfactor" to the ArmSway pendulum input to have the arms move with your breathing!

There are controls for the speed & amount of breathing around this Message box. Change the values if you want to adjust the animation, or set to 0 to turn different controls off.

This graph animates the Chest and Upper Chest bones (rotation and scale), and the Root bone (position). If your model doesn't have a root bone, or it's named differently, you will have to rename the red Object Position node on the far right. If you're experiencing weirdness, try setting some of the controls to 0 to turn them off. There are also compability parameters below you can try to use. If you need any help feel free to dm me on twitter or discord!
====================
=== PARAMETERS ===

BreathSpeed
- Breathing cycle time
- 1 is approximately a 6 second loop

BreathRotation (Blue)
- Applies to UpperChest and Chest bones
- Amount of rotation backwards (to emphasize breathing by leaning the body back) 
- NOTE: if animating your model's bones doesn't work well, feel free to remove the Additive Bone Rotation nodes (colour-coded in blue)

BreathMovement (Red)
- Applies to Root Y position
- This lifts the whole model up slightly (will trigger ArmSway arm movement!)
- NOTE: if your model has a different name for a root bone, rename this in the Object Position Node to whichever bone will uniformly move your model's position

BreathScale (Cyan)
- Applies to Chest bone, and will scale up everything above (including arms, head, props/accessories attached to head, etc)
- Will increase and decrease by +/- Value
- Can sometimes behave strangely depending on your model.


=== NOTES ===

- If you have different animations for your model, it's possible they may behave strangely with this graph. In those cases, try using the toggle to turn off the breathing when animations are active.

- This graph attempts to use your armature's Root bone to move your model up and down. This may be named differently for you. Adjust the Object Position node with your models armature root bone name.

- "Maintain Hip Pos" in the ARKit settings can sometimes interact strangely with some of these settings. If you're experiencing weirdness, try adjusting this setting.

====================

Thanks to Nile for help!
Video tutorial by Kana Fuyuko: https://youtu.be/3I75oqczTHQ

<size=20>Graph Toggle</size>

BreathActive turns the node graph on or off, which can be toggled by the hotkeysThese nodes reset the bones when the graph is turned off.

<size=20>Animation Nodes</size>

Main nodes for the Bone Rotations (Blue), Root movement (Red), and Bone Scales (Cyan).

If any of the control parameters are set to 0, those respective nodes are fully turned off (with bone resets).

The parameter values calculated to the left are combined with the compatability parameters first.

<size=20>Math Logic</size>

1. All the input parameters are loaded, including the compatibility nodes.
2. BreathTime is calculated is calculated as a looping value from 0 to 360 (using the modulus), with the increase based on BreathSpeed
3. BreathFactor is calculated as sin(BreathTime), converting the number to -1 to 1. BreathFactor will control the timing of the breath loop for our parameters.
4. BreathRotation is calculated as the negative (so it rotates backwards) scaled by BreathFactor.
5. BreathMovement is calculated by dividing by 100 (since we only want small movement) scaled by BreathFactor.
6. BreathScale is calculated by dividing by 100, scaled by Breath Factor, plus 1 (so that the initial scale is 1)

<size=20>COMPATIBILITY NODES</size> Import parameters from other node graphs.This graph animates the Chest and Upper Chest bones (rotation and scale), and the Root bone (position) VNyan will overwrite these nodes if they are also used by other graphs.If you have other graphs that use these nodes, put the respective parameter names from those graphs below to carry them forward. This works best if this graph comes before others.

=== NOTES ===
If this graph comes BEFORE other graphs with conflicting nodes, this graph will overwrite the others, and the nodes below should work for compatability.If this graph comes AFTER other graphs with conflicting nodes, those graphs will overwrite this one, and the nodes below WON'T WORK. 

In that case, you can try three things: change the ordering of your graphs, work in compatability into the other graphs, or change the timer name "BreathTimer" to match the conflicting graph. (When graphs have the same name, the nodes controlled by the Timer node last in order takes priority.)
=== EXTRA NOTES ===
For clarity about what's happening:- Additive Bone Rotation nodes targeting the same bone overwrite each other.
- If two graphs use separately named timers that occur simultaneously, the timer created first gives priority to which Additive Bone Rotation node overwrites the other.
- If two graphs use the same named timer, the Timer node created last gives priority.
- Graph order will dictate which the order that timers or Timer nodes are created.

<size=20>OUTPUT PARAMETERS</size>

List of the animation parameters this graph uses, if you need to carry over these parameters to other graphs.Bone Rotation - UpperChest Rotation Y = [BreathRotationParam]
Bone Rotation - Chest Rotation Y = [BreathRotationParam]

Object Position - "Root" Position Y = [BreathMovementParam]

Bone Scale - Chest Scale X = [BreathScaleParam]
Bone Scale - Chest Scale Y = [BreathScaleParam]
Bone Scale - Chest Scale Z = [BreathScaleParam]

HeartRate Monitor If you have Pulsoid heart rate active, it should increase your breathing as your heart rate increases. Logic BreathSpeed works out such that a complete breath happens every 6 seconds at 60FPS (Note that this dependent on fps, so a faster fps means it'll run faster!) Linking HeartRate Respiration Rate (rr) is the number of complete breaths per minute The ratio between heartrate:respirationrate is 4:1 So 60hr:15rr, 80hr:20rr, 120hr:30rr We can simply take the heart rate, divide by 40, and use this value as the breathspeed!
